that have been genetically optimized by individual selection--such as photosynthesis and drought tolerance--are bad candidates for genetic improvement. Traits like plant height and leaf angle, which determine the collective performance of plant communities, offer more room for improvement. Agriculturalists can also benefit from more sophisticated comparisons among natural communities and from the study of wild species in the landscapes where they evolved. Darwinian Agriculture reveals why it is sometimes better to slow or even reverse evolutionary trends when they are inconsistent with our present goals, and how we can glean new ideas from natural selection's marvelous innovations in wild species.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAgricultural biotechnology. 0aCropsxEvolution. 0aEvolution (Biology). 0aSustainable agriculture. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Horticulture.2bisacsh  aColin Donald.  aGreen Revolution.  aadaptation.  aagricultural ecosystems.  aagricultural research.  aagriculture.  aagroecologists.  aagroecology.  aanimals.  abet-hedging.  abiodiversity.  abiotechnology.  acheating.  achemicals.  acompetition.  acomplementarity.  aconflict.  acooperation.  acotton farmers.  acrop diversity.  acrops.  acultivation.  adrought tolerance.  aenvironmental impact.  aevolution.  aevolutionary arms races.  aevolutionary biology.  afarmers.  afood production.  afood security.  afood supply.  afungus-growing ants.  agenes.  agenetic engineering.  agenetic improvement.  agroup selection.  aintercropping.  akin selection.  aleaf-cutter ants.  amultispecies interactions.  amutualism.  anatural ecosystems.  anatural selection.  anitrogen fixation.  anutrient-use efficiency.  anutrients.  aperennial grain crops.  apest cont